🔒 Encapsulation

Encapsulation is about bundling data (variables) and methods (functions) together and restricting direct access to some parts of an object.

Key idea:

👉 “Hide internal details and control access.”

How it’s done in JS:
Using closures
Using private fields (#) in classes
Using getters and setters
Example:
class BankAccount {
  #balance = 0; // private field

  deposit(amount) {
    this.#balance += amount;
  }

  getBalance() {
    return this.#balance;
  }
}

const acc = new BankAccount();
acc.deposit(100);
console.log(acc.getBalance()); // 100
// console.log(acc.#balance); ❌ Error (private)

✅ Here, #balance is hidden from outside → encapsulation.

🎭 Data Abstraction

Data abstraction is about showing only essential features and hiding complex implementation details.

Key idea:

👉 “Expose what is necessary, hide how it works.”

How it’s done in JS:
Using functions or classes with simple interfaces
Hiding complex logic inside methods
Example:
class CoffeeMachine {
  makeCoffee() {
    this.#boilWater();
    this.#brewCoffee();
    console.log("Coffee is ready!");
  }

  #boilWater() {
    console.log("Boiling water...");
  }

  #brewCoffee() {
    console.log("Brewing coffee...");
  }
}

const machine = new CoffeeMachine();
machine.makeCoffee(); 

✅ User just calls makeCoffee() without knowing internal steps → abstraction.

⚖️ Key Differences
Feature	Encapsulation	Data Abstraction
Purpose	Protect data	Simplify complexity
Focus	Restrict access	Hide implementation
Achieved by	Private fields, closures	Interfaces, public methods
User sees	Controlled access to data	Only essential features
Example analogy	Capsule (data + methods together)	Remote control (simple interface)
🧠 Simple Way to Remember
Encapsulation = “Protect data” 🔒
Abstraction = “Hide complexity” 🎭